04595nam a22006015i 9780822381792DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19931993ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223817927 a10.1515/97808223817922doi  a(DE-B1597)553346  a(OCoLC)892950078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPA3978b.S5 1993 7aDRA0060002bisacsh04a882/.012201 aSegal, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEuripides and the Poetics of Sorrow :bArt, Gender, and Commemoration in ‹i›Alcestis, Hippolytus‹/i›, and ‹i›Hecuba‹/i› /cCharles Segal. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Euripides' Muse of Sorrows and the Artifice of Tragic Pleasure -- tAlcestis -- t3. Cold Delight: Art, Death, and Transgression of Genre -- t4. Female Death and Male Tears -- t5. Admetus' Divided House: Spatial Dichotomies and Gender Roles -- tHippolytus -- t6. Language, Signs, and Gender -- t7. Theater, Ritual, and Commemoration -- t8. Confusion and Concealment: Vision, Hope, and Tragic Knowledge -- tHecuba -- t9. Golden Armor and Servile Robes: Heroism and Metamorphosis -- t10. Violence and the Other: Greek, Female, and Barbarian -- t11. Law and Universals -- t12. The Problem of the Gods -- t13. Conclusion: Euripides' Songs of Sorrow -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhere is the pleasure in tragedy? This question, how suffering and sorrow become the stuff of aesthetic delight, is at the center of Charles Segal's new book, which collects and expands his recent explorations of Euripides' art.Alcestis, Hippolytus, and Hecuba, the three early plays interpreted here, are linked by common themes of violence, death, lamentation and mourning, and by their implicit definitions of male and female roles. Segal shows how these plays draw on ancient traditions of poetic and ritual commemoration, particularly epic song, and at the same time refashion these traditions into new forms. In place of the epic muse of martial glory, Euripides, Segal argues, evokes a muse of sorrows who transforms the suffering of individuals into a "common grief for all the citizens," a community of shared feeling in the theater.Like his predecessors in tragedy, Euripides believes death, more than any other event, exposes the deepest truth of human nature. Segal examines the revealing final moments in Alcestis, Hippolytus, and Hecuba, and discusses the playwright's use of these deaths--especially those of women--to question traditional values and the familiar definitions of male heroism. Focusing on gender, the affective dimension of tragedy, and ritual mourning and commemoration, Segal develops and extends his earlier work on Greek drama. The result deepens our understanding of Euripides' art and of tragedy itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAlcestis (Greek mythology) in literature. 0aGrief in literature. 0aHecuba (Legendary character) in literature. 0aHippolytus (Greek mythology) in literature. 0aSex role in literature. 0aTragedy. 0aTrojan WarxLiterature and the war. 7aDRAMA / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822381792zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822381792423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822381792.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles